{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"d82682b5-3df2-4728-a107-033fd4d72ce6","content":"Here's how to collect a trace from a .NET 8 app in a Windows container on K8s:\n\n**1. Exec into the container:**\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod-name> -- powershell\n```\n\n**2. Install `dotnet-trace`:**\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n```\n\n**3. Find your process ID:**\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n**4. Collect the trace:**\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --duration 00:00:30 --profile cpu-sampling\n```\n\n**5. Copy the `.nettrace` file out:**\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod-name>:<path-to-file> ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n**6. Analyze** by opening the `.nettrace` in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or convert it to Speedscope format:\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace convert trace.nettrace --format speedscope\n```\n\n> **Tip:** If `dotnet tool install` fails (no SDK in the container), download the standalone `dotnet-trace` from the [.NET diagnostics releases](https://github.com/dotnet/diagnostics) or copy it in via `kubectl cp`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"1483b071-6fb0-411c-bfb9-cfd7a83d2a8e","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a .NET performance trace from a Windows container running on Kubernetes. This is a diagnostic/troubleshooting question, not a code change request. I'll provide concise, actionable steps.","outputTokens":373,"requestId":"D819:1D9368:806106:93E589:69FBE995"},"id":"9d80f8df-af65-492a-b7f1-25c0a81f3f42","timestamp":"2026-05-07T01:23:42.149Z","parentId":"0cbd1dd0-6e42-426f-b701-7f258120f2f3"}
